Name: National Museum of Singapore
Address: 93 Stamford Road National Museum of Singapore, Singapore 178897
Review1: "We enjoyed learning about the history of Singapore. It allows for an understanding of the many cultures of Singapore and the interesting journey to their present time."
Review2: "This is a well thought out, creatively presented history of Singapore, that is LOTS of fun. Highly recommended."

Name: National Gallery Singapore
Review1:
"The large and imposing National Gallery, comprising the former City Hall AND Supreme Court Buildings, promises a lot with its appearance (and price of entry, S$30 for a tourist for all exhibits).

But that promise mostly fell flat. A lot of the art on display was aggressively mundane. The space didn’t feel tastefully laid out, but rather over-stretched, straining to meet the promise of the size and the presumed wealth of the government sponsoring it.

The special exhibition from Nam June Paik (early 2022) was quite great and was the sole highlight of note"
Review2: "With a wide range of exhibits, be prepared to spend at least half a day, if not longer here. General admission is free for locals, with some special exhibits which require fees (although these are free for students and teachers)."

Name: Lee Kong Chian Natural History Museum
Review1:
"While it seems like the museum is not too large at first. We spent around 2.5 hours walking the entire thing simply because it was information rich.

Some of the exhibits are duplicated throughout the entire museum but otherwise, it was informative."
Review2:
"As the title, I never know we have a museum with dinosaur bones. Didn’t really read the write out so I am not sure if these are fossils or constructed.

Other than the dinosaur, it’s has been an enlightening trip as we get to learn about the various flora and fauna of Singapore. The write outs are not too long nor too short. Just detailed enough to entice one to read, and enough exhibits such that the trip is not boring."

Name: Museum of Ice Cream Singapore
Review1: "Do NOT miss this place when you're in Singapore! And the vibe of the staff is crazy! Loved every minute!"
Review2: "Great experience for a couple. Had a great time with my wife here. She really loves every station and every icecream provided. Sprinkle room is the most enjoyable."

Name: Battlebox
Review1: "Visited my family earlier this year for the first time since they moved to Singapore in 2020. They recommended I take the guided tour of Battlebox and I am so glad I did. The guide was extremely knowledgeable and very pleasant. The tour explains a lot about the British surrender to the Japanese and it was all the more interesting as you were in the very rooms where the decision to surrender was taken. One of the highlights of my trip."
Review2: "The battlebox bunker is a great site to visit if you are into military history or curious about what is under Fort Canning Park. It’s a fascinating structure and the guided tour component offers some context and background behind what happened here in 1942. Keep in mind photos are not allowed in the bunker. The tour is around 30 minutes with a guide to specific rooms, and then you are allowed to roam the bunker at your own pace. Altogether I spent just over an hour on site, so one could consider this a quick stop while exploring Singapore."

Name: Singapore Flyer
Review1: "It boasts of being bigger than the London Eye, but only just. And in every other aspect, it is inferior. The Flyer has been plagued by technical problems since the start."
Review2: "One of the worst managed attractions in Singapore. They do not inform you on their website that there may be a 3 hours wait even though you pre-purchased you ticket. They do not allow you to select a time slot while booking. There are snaking queues and the 1 meter social distancing is not followed. Worst experience in efficient Singapore"

Name: Science Centre
Review1: "Last time I visited this place in my childhood. That time there was lots of interesting things. Still can remember that dummy Einstein was giving lectures.. There was one real chopper can rotate the rare fan. Full flight experience of Singapore Airlines. Now a days they have improved, its true. Lots of things can be enjoyed. Finally it's a nice place to learn with enjoyment."
Review2:
"I called the Singapore Science Centre's Customer Service Number to confirm the prices for my Family (Dependent and Employment Pass Holders).

The lady that answered the phone must of been upset / angry that she was required to work on New Year's Eve as she was incredibly unfriendly.

This place does not recognise EP, S-Pass or Dependant Pass Holder's meaning we are required to pay "tourist" prices. Perhaps the only attraction in Singapore that does this.

Avoid if you are a EP, S-Pass or Dependant Pass Holder."

Name: IFly
Review1: "Pathetic experience and service. They mislead customers into believing it’s a 1.5 hr activity when actually it’s only 45 secs! They mislead customers by saying you will go from 12k to 3k feet but hide the fact that it’s only available to their Challenger package, not their entry level package (who just float at 3 feet lol). The website lacks all of these info. Recommend never to visit this place,"
Review2: "Writing this on behalf of our helper who received it as a gift for her birthday and said she'd like to leave a good review. Instructor Darryl was very patient and clear, felt completely safe throughout the whole experience (but still found it thrilling). Enjoyed the feeling of free fall; watching more experienced flyers, and taking videos. Much thanks to the staff for making it so pleasant. Glad we got this for her as a birthday gift."

Name: Skyline Luge Sentosa
Review1: "This attraction is 100% worth every penny and a must do at sentosa. I did this with my toddler daughter and she enjoyed it a lot. So did I. I am giving 4 instead of 5 because the camera for skyline was not working. It flashed and we smiled at camera every time but during check out they said its not working. Even the photos from luge ride was not clicked as per our expectations."
Review2: "If you are going to Sentosa, then you have to hit this one up. This is BEYOND fun. Taking the cable car to the starting point is also part of the experience. Racecar tracks move aside! This is better."

Name: Wild Wild Wet
Review1:
"Community-style waterpark with a decent selection of fun slides for all age groups. We went during the week and waiting times were moderate to short. The wave pool was nice for the kids as well and during our visit staff handed out waterpistols to celebrate the water festival Sonkran. Staff is making sure everyone is safe and adheres to the minimum height applicable at each slide.

The park would benefit from a renovation though and it’s definitely not the right place to go if you look for a resort-style high-end experience. It’s a great down-to-earth place for waterplay, not a luxury retreat. The locker rooms and changing area reminded me a bit of public swimming pools in my hometown in Germany."
Review2: "Excellent customer service! Smooth arrangements from the booking till the visit. Ivy and team gave me and family a wonderful experience in WIld Wild Wet. The cabanas are so comfortable ad decorated with the beauriful decoration for my son birthday. We definitely will come back again!"

Name: SuperPark Singapore
Address: #02-477, Suntec City (North Wing, 3 Temasek Blvd, Tower 1, Singapore 038983
Review1: "By the end of the day, my energy was all drained. Mainly because I had fun playing all sorts of activities there. Maybe due to the fact it is COVID period, the time limit was just right for me to try out all of the stuff provided. And it is quite affordable too! Good experience! Would go again in the future with more people."
Review2: "I had fun at SuperPark Singapore, the staff are friendly, big space and a lot of fun outdoor activities to do indoors."

Name: HydroDash
Review1: "Fantastic fun, with some extremely nice staff! Definitely worth a visit for all ages, with good safety instructions too."
Review2: "Its okay.. very fun with my friend.. everything smooth and controlable.. advise to ware the water-shoe to more grip.. unfortunately the guys as safeguard spoil our mood when we want to jump for the last one before back but didn’t."

Name: Snow City Singapore
Review1: "Will never step foot again. The snow looks like it’s 100 years old. Yellow brown snow? Disgusting. The place looks so so outdated. Only 2 things were available for play. One slide and bumper car."
Review2:
"Bought 2hrs ticket from KKday, and booked 2-4pm slot for myself and my 3yo nephew
As per snowcity website, jacket and snow boots are complimentary..we paid for the gloves as it is really cold inside

Best for little kids to wear waterproof pants (&bring extra socks! As the fake snow will get into their shoes and wet their socks)

The place was not well maintained, jacket had spoilt zips and incorrect sizes were given to us (eg: my nephew shoes was 28&29, and he got two left handed gloves)
But the little one didn’t care about the fittings and had fun in the cold

As we had belongings, we would need to pay 2 x $1 for one locker and if you need water, we need to repay the $2 for the locker which was abit troublesome and costly
Our 2nd locker couldn’t admit the 2nd $1 coin, and doesn’t allow refund of the 1st $1 coin. The staff had to come and give us another locker.

We didn’t buy tickets for the bumper car, we thought we can buy at the ride area, but we had to exit to the main reception and purchase the tickets before heading back in.
The pathway was narrow and slippery, and the ride was less than 5mins!"

Name: Haw Par Villa
Review1:
"Great day out experience - feast for eyes, mouth and mind.

In conjunction with the Singapore Heritage Fest, visited the Tiger Car experience and then the Tiger Tiger Burning Bright walk.

Then had a lovely lunch at the Sixth Milestone Cafe.

After a nice walk amongst the 1000+ sculptures, it was time for a journey to Hell's Museum. The rebranded museum is now ticketed but a great experience, if you can join the guided tour, but even nice, otherwise.

And did I add, the ticket comes with a free veggie bee Hoon ??.

I would like to compliment Miss Kimberly who hosted the Hell's Museum tour as well as Madam Yin Wah who took us on the Tiger Walk.

And special mention to Mr Jeya from Journeys Pte Ltd and his team of volunteers.

A day well spent."
Review2: "A great theme park close to the MRT and free. Set up by the family that amongst other things created Tiger Balm. They created the park in 1937 to show Chinese mythology and history and has had a few issues in the past, but now free for all. A very different place to visit not what we were expecting, but fun and well worth the visit. There are other exhibits that give the history of the family and the development of Tiger Balm and how the brothers developed it and using sales techniques sold it world wide. I loved the cars, definitely a Tiger in that tank. The background information was informative and I learnt a lot that day, so was educated and entertained. There are also details on the development of Haw Par Villa its design and it history and final destruction. Well worth the visit and I'm sure it would be great t night, but not for me! Also after the theme park visit Hell's Museum, but there is a cost to that but well worth it and its got AC."

Name: Skypark Sentosa by AJ Hackett
Address: 30 Siloso Beach Walk, Sentosa Island, Singapore 099011
Review1: "It was my first bungy jump and it didnt disappoint.. The crew was awesome, friendly and warm. I couldnt bring myself to jump when i was at the edge but their kind words really helped. It was exhilirating and out of this world and i loved it!"
Review2:
"Was too scared to go for the bungy jump so we opted for the cheaper and less terrifying giant swing. Was a little bit lost on how to get from the counters downstairs to the giant swing queue upstairs, but was provided directions by a staff that saw our confusion.

Service provided by the staff at the giant swing was excellent! They were friendly and made jokes to reduce our anxiety. The whole ride itself was WOOSH.

The only feedback I have to further improve their service would be to help idiots like me to better understand how to strap on the go-pro. Since I am a go-pro noob, our footage turned out completely disastrous, HAHAHA. The camera wasn't even pointed at us, T_T."

Name: Lion City Bike Tour Singapore
Review1: "Had a great tour of Singapore this morning. Jeff was a fantastic guide, the tour was informative and fun. Would definitely recommend. Hope to do one of his other tours when next in Singapore."
Review2: "Fred is an amazing tour guide. Has good knowledge of Singaporean history and creates a really memorable experience that enriches all the sites that you see."

Name: Universal Studios Singapore
Review1:
"We had been to Universal in LA a couple of times but that was a longtime ago. So great to get a chance to go with my grandkids. And we had a good day, it really is about the kids for these places.

We really enjoyed the Jurassic river ride (after a wait for the queue) a big surorise at the end. The Shrek 4D was fantastic, don't miss that. I kids enjoyed the roller coaster in Far far away land.

Not all the stuff was open, not sure when it will be. Covid restrictions and staffing I guess."
Review2:
"We went for the day to universal studios. Two adults. Cost per person €81.
The park isn’t opening until 12 which we couldn’t only figure must be staffing issues, later discussed with the customer service.
There are a significant number of shops, rides and restaurants closed in the park. Some say for maintenance, some just say closed. This is not advertised when you book your tickets at the front of the park and certainly not reflected in the price. The atmosphere in the park is empty, no characters, no parades happening. As a result of things being closed the queues are longer for the open rides.

I genuinely couldn’t wait for my day out at universal and was so disappointed.

We spoke with customer services who said they wouldn’t refund due to company terms and conditions, but would send us in with an express ticket to get on rides quicker. But the fun was gone. It was a total waste of time."

Name: Singapore Cable Car
Address: 109 Mount Faber Rd, Mount Faber Peak, Singapore 099203
Review1: "For as low as $3.00 (limited time offer) you can ride on the cable car, this is only for the SG residents and applicable on Sentosa Line. It was great fun bringing my little boy. He actually practices his color recognition with the help of the colorful cabins. You can maximize your ride by boarding from Imbiah Station then alight to Siloso Beach and wander around in Fort Siloso then go back again to the cable car to finish your one round trip. It’s good to have a break to avoid feeling dizzy. And if unsure, just approach the staff, they are friendly and happy to help."
Review2:
"It's always an amazing view and quite a cool way to go to the beach.

It's a few stations on the way to the ocean.

It's quite chill inside of the cabin so don't worry that you will get hot ??.

You have to change the cabin a few times every station they staff will ask you to re-enter

Get your camera ready and enjoy the day ahead

Cheers"

Name: East Coast Park
Address: 906 EAST COAST PARKWAY EAST COAST PARK OFFICE SINGAPORE 449895
Review1: "Good place to visit with family, however, the park is very dirty, dirty bench and unclean grass. Can’t swim in sea, it’s a slope, steep, you can dip and stand only or go very deep. Marine cove area has decent food options and children play area is good."
Review2:
"Just the place to go to relax by the sea side where the gentle sea breeze and wafting waves of the sea give you the perfect setting to walk, jog or run in relaxed style unhindered in sheer abandon!
Memorable evening we spent last week.
Will certainly come again.
Do give it a try!"
